					I think Starrett has Sales Issues.

If I was Head Honcho @ Starrett, I would get drunk with the guys who did Harley Davidson's sales turnaround.

I love motorcycles, but I know I would kill myself on one - I am not a biker.

But I have a great admiration for the way Harley played their Strong Suit  in their advertizing camapaigns.

"An American Legend"  and so it is. We all have brothers or cousins who rode Harleys even if we didn't.

For many of older guys, Motorcycle meant Harley Davidson (or Indian).

So, too wth Starrett (and Brown and Sharpe).

Any of us who take pride in being a machinist or in doing machine work will gladly pay the ilttle bit more for a Starrett.

Where is Starrett's Presence??

You see Harley's logo everywhere.

Where are the Starrtt Coffee cups, the Decimal equivalent charts, the note pads around the shop, the calendars? How about stickers for the window of your vehicle?  And Starrett "T" shirts? (with pockets, Don)

"World's Greatest Toolmakers" should be visible everywhere around any shop where metal is cut and neasured.

I have "The Starrett Book for Student Machinists" in the handbook drawer of my tool chest. (1945 edition)

If they aren't publishing the revised edition, then they should.

Starrett, Brown and Share and Lufkin had their tool board displays in glass cases hanging at all their distributors' shops and in the class rooms of the trade schools.

I don't see them any more - why??

Sales, Sales, Sales!

Starrett not only has to Make the world's greatest tools, they have to SELL the world's greatest tools.

They won't do that by keeping their light under a bushel.

They have one BIG advantage - MEN buy tools.

Harley appeals to men. They are expensive bikes, but they Sell!

Weatherby makes rifles that appeal to men. They are not Wal Mart Specials, but they sell well

Automakers sell Pick 'em Ups to men.
Pick ups are selling better than cars these days.

Starrett's ad campaign should be a No Brainer.

I wouldn't be caught dead making a fine measurement without a Starrett or older Brown and Sharpe tool, It's a man thing, it's  reputation thing.

We are right back to where we always get, If Starrett has problems, the problems aren't with Starrett's foreign competition, the problems are with Starrett.










